        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Although the extent of the water emission (or absorption in the case of the thermal lines of H2O observed with Herschel) is unknown, we could expect an upper size of 2" corresponding to the observed size of the molecular emission in HCN, HCO+, and CO and the large resolvable scale structures could be around 0.3-0.4". The size of the individual clouds contributing to the 183.3 and 325.15 GHz emission is probably much smaller, of the order of 0.1-0.3" from Herschel modeling of the water lines. Therefore, we will need an angular resolution of 0.05'', which is provided by the most extended configuration of ALMA in Cycle3, in order to resolve the water emission at 325.15 GHz in Arp220. 

We propose to use channels 7.8 km/s wide to reach a S/N ratio &gt;10 in the line wings. The observed emission with the 30m IRAM radio telescope is 120 mJy at the line center and decreases to 25 mJy at velocities of 250 km/s from the line center. We request for a sensitivity over 7.8 km/s channels of 1.15 mJy corresponding to 5.5 K over a beam of 0.05". We do expect the water emission to be clumpy and not distributed over more than ~4 beams in individual channels. In the worst case we would get S/N&gt;6. However, the line is 600 km/s wide, hence, some additional spectral smoothing could be done to improve the S/N in the line wings if needed. 

The total observing time is 1.92 h.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have selected to basebands of 1.875 GHz separated by 1.6 GHz to cover the whole extent of the 325.15 GHz water vapour emission (600 km/s) redshifted to 319.3 GHz. Spectral averaging to 8 channels will be aceptable given the broad linewidth of the observed lines.
Two additional basebands are placed in the lower frequency band to get the continuum with the same angular resolution than the line which is absolutely necessary to model the radiative transfert of H2O in Arp220 (dust emission pumping of molecular lines).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular extent of water emission in Arp220 is unknown but the best models seem to indicate the presence of clumps of 0.1-0.3" in size. Hence, the requested angular resolution of 0.05" could permit to map and resolve these clumps. The largest angular size we could expect for H2O in Arp220 is 2" for the whole linewidth based on interferometric maps of CO, HCN and other molecular species. The largest scale structures we expect are around 0.3-0.5" for a given velocity channel.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
